A060681.name: Largest difference between consecutive divisors of n (ordered by size).
formula: a(n) = n - A032742(n). - _Omar E. Pol_, Aug 31 2011

A060682.name: Number of distinct differences between consecutive divisors of n (ordered by size).

A060683.name: Numbers for which the differences between consecutive divisors (ordered by size) are distinct.

A060684.name: Smallest difference between consecutive divisors (ordered by size) of 2n+1.

A060685.name: Largest difference between consecutive divisors (ordered by size) of 2n+1.

A060687.name: Numbers n such that there exist exactly 2 Abelian groups of order n, i.e., A000688(n) = 2.
formula: Cohen proved that a(n) = kn + O(sqrt(n) log log n), where k = A013661/A179119 = 1/A271971 = 4.981178... - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 02 2016

A060688.name: Number of dissimilar ternary squarefree words of length n+1.

A060689.name: Number of non-Abelian groups of order n.

A060690.name: a(n) = binomial(2^n + n - 1, n).
formula: G.f.: A(x) = Sum_{n>=0} [ -log(1 - 2^n*x)]^n / n!. More generally, Sum_{n>=0} [ -log(1 - q^n*x)]^n/n! = Sum_{n>=0} C(q^n+n-1,n)*x^n ; also Sum_{n>=0} log(1 + q^n*x)^n/n! = Sum_{n>=0} C(q^n,n)*x^n. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Dec 29 2007

A060691.name: Expansion of AGM(1,1-8x) (where AGM denotes the arithmetic-geometric mean).
formula: a(n) ~ -Pi * 2^(3*n-1) / (n * log(n)^2) * (1 - (2*gamma + 4*log(2))/log(n) + (3*gamma^2 + 12*log(2)*gamma + 12*log(2)^2 - Pi^2/2) / log(n)^2), where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Sep 29 2019

A060692.name: Number of parts if 3^n is partitioned into parts of size 2^n as far as possible and into parts of size 1^n.
formula: For n > 2, a(n) = 3^n mod (2^n-1). [_Alex Ratushnyak_, Jul 22 2012]

A060693.name: Triangle (0 <= k <= n) read by rows: T(n, k) is the number of Schröder paths from (0,0) to (2n,0) having k peaks.
formula: Triangle T(n, k) (0 <= k <= n) read by rows; given by [1, 1, 1, 1, 1, ...] DELTA [1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, ...] where DELTA is the operator defined in A084938. - _Philippe Deléham_, Aug 12 2003

If C_n(x) is the g.f. of row n of the Narayana numbers (A001263), C_n(x) = Sum_{k=1..n}(binomial(n,k-1)binomial(n-1,k-1)/k * x^k) and T_n(x) is the g.f. of row n of T(n,k), then T_n(x) = C_n(x+1), or T(n,k) = [x^n]Sum_{k=1..n}(A001263(n,k)*(x+1)^k). - _Mitch Harris_, Jan 16 2007, Jan 31 2007
T(n, k) = binomial(2n-k, n)*binomial(n, k)/(n-k+1). - _Philippe Deléham_, Dec 07 2003
A060693(n, k) = binomial(2*n-k, k)*A000108(n-k); A000108: Catalan numbers. - _Philippe Deléham_, Dec 30 2003
With F(x,t) = (1-(2+t)*x-sqrt(1-2*(2+t)*x+(t*x)^2))/(2*x) an o.g.f. (nulling the n=0 term) in x for the A060693 polynomials in t,
G(x,t) = x/(1+t+(2+t)*x+x^2) is the compositional inverse in x.

Consequently, with H(x,t) = 1/(dG(x,t)/dx)=(1+t+(2+t)*x+x^2)^2 /(1+t-x^2), the n-th A060693 polynomial in t is given by (1/n!)*[(H(x,t)*d/dx)^n] x evaluated at x=0, i.e., F(x,t) = exp[x*H(u,t)*d/du] u, evaluated at u = 0.
See my 2008 formulas in A033282 to relate this entry to A088617, A001263, A086810, and other matrices. - _Tom Copeland_, Jan 22 2016
Rows of this entry are non-vanishing antidiagonals of A097610. See p. 14 of Agapito et al. for a bivariate generating function and its inverse. - _Tom Copeland_, Feb 03 2016

A060694.name: A triangle related to rooted trees.
formula: E.g.f. given by the Maple expression RootOf(-exp(_Z*x*t)+x*t*exp(_Z*x*t)+y*t*exp(-_Z+_Z*x*t)-y*t^2*x*exp(-_Z+_Z*x*t)+1-t+t*exp(-_Z+_Z*x*t)-x*t*exp(-_Z+_Z*x*t));

A060695.name: a(n) = gcd(2n, A060766(2n)).
formula: a(n) = a(2k) is either n = 2k or n/2 = k. a(n) = n/2 seems regular, a(n) = n seems "anomalous".

A060696.name: Number of permutations in S_n avoiding the strings 123, 321 and 231.
formula: E.g.f. for A(n)=a(n+1) (n>=0): (1+x)*exp(x^2/2)*(1+sqrt(Pi/2)*erf(x/sqrt(2))), where erf denotes the error function. - Antonio G. Astudillo (afg_astudillo(AT)hotmail.com), Nov 01 2002

A060697.name: The sum of the first n composite numbers plus 1 is a prime.

A060698.name: The sum of the first n composite numbers minus 1 is a prime.

A060699.name: a(n) = floor(A^(C^n)), where A = 2.084551112207285611..., C = 1.221.
formula: a(n) = floor(A^(C^n)); A = 2.084551112... ; C = 1.221. - Luis Rodriguez-Torres (ludovicusmagister(AT)yahoo.com), Feb 10 2009

A060700.name: "Anomalous" numbers k such that for even numbers 2k, gcd(2k, lcm(dd(2k)))=2k and not k, where dd(2k) is the first difference set of divisors of 2k.

A060701.name: Table by antidiagonals of Mahonian numbers T(n,k): permutations of n letters with k inversions.
formula: Product (1+x+...+x^k), k=1..n-1 = Sum T(n, k)x^k, k=0..n(n-1)/2.

A060702.name: Orders of finite groups that have trivial center.

A060703.name: Negative values of 2*x*y^4 + x^2*y^3 - 2*x^3*y*2 - x^4*y - y^5 + 2*y for x,y >= 0.

A060704.name: Singular n X n matrices over GF(2).

A060705.name: Singular n X n matrices over GF(3).

A060706.name: For n >= 1 a(n) is the size of the conjugacy class in the symmetric group S_(4n) consisting of permutations whose cycle decomposition is a product of n disjoint 4-cycles.
formula: a(n) = (4n)! / (n! * 4^n). Recursion: a(0) = 1, a(1) = 6, for n >= 2 a(n) = a(n-1) * C(4n - 1, 3)* 6 = a(n-1)*(4n-1)*(4n-2)*(4n-3). Using Stirling's formula in A000142 we have a(n) ~ 2 * 64^n * (n/e)^(3n).

Write the generating function for this sequence in the form A(x) = sum_{n>=0} a(n)* x^(3*n+1)/(3*n+1)!. Then A'(x)*( 1 - A(x)^3) = 1, consequently A(x) is a root of z^4 - 4*z + 4*x with A(0) = 0. Cf. A052502. - _Peter Bala_, Jan 02 2015

A060707.name: Base-60 (Babylonian or sexagesimal) expansion of Pi.

A060709.name: Continued fraction expansion of the Reuleaux Triangle constant.

A060710.name: Number of subgroups of dihedral group with 2n elements, counting conjugate subgroups only once, i.e., conjugacy classes of subgroups of the dihedral group.
formula: For odd n: a(n) = tau(2n) = 2*tau(n)= 2*A000005(n). - Ahmed Fares (ahmedfares(AT)my-deja.com), Jul 12 2001
Moebius transform is period 2 sequence [2, 3, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 20 2005

A060711.name: Smallest number whose digit sum is n^4.

A060712.name: Smallest number whose digit sum is 3^n.

A060713.name: Smallest number whose digit sum is 5^n.

A060714.name: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-1 minus the number of terms of the same parity as n so far).

A060715.name: Number of primes between n and 2n exclusive.

A060716.name: Singular n X n matrices over GF(4).

A060717.name: Degrees of irreducible representations of alternating group A_14.

A060719.name: a(0) = 1; a(n+1) = a(n) + Sum_{i=0..n} binomial(n,i)*(a(i)+1).
formula: Equals the binomial transform of A186021. Also, a(n) = A186021(n+1) - 1. - _Gary W. Adamson_ May 20 2013

A060720.name: Singular n X n matrices over GF(5).

A060721.name: Singular n X n matrices over GF(7).

A060723.name: a(n) is the denominator of r(n) where r(n) is the sequence of rational numbers defined by the recursion: r(0) = 0, r(1) = 1 and for n>1 r(n) = r(n-1) + r(n-2)/2. From this definition it is clear that a(n) is always a power of 2 (see A060755).

A060724.name: Number of subgroups of the group C_n X C_n (where C_n is the cyclic group of order n).
formula: a(n) is multiplicative: if the canonical factorization of n is the product of p^e(p) over primes then a(n) = product a(p^e(p)). For a prime p: a(p) = p + 3.
a(n) = Sum_{i|n, j|n} gcd(i, j). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Oct 28 2001
Also a(n) = Sum_{d|n} d*tau((n/d)^2). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 01 2002
Inverse Moebius transform of A060648. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 31 2009
Dirichlet g.f. zeta^3(s)*zeta(s-1)/zeta(2*s). - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 14 2011
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} psi(d)*tau(n/d), where psi is A001615 and tau is A000005. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Feb 29 2012
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 5 * Pi^2 * n^2 / 24. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jun 02 2019

A060725.name: E.g.f.: exp(-(x^5/5))/(1-x).
formula: The formula for a(n) is: a(n) = n! * sum i=0 ... [ n/5 ]( (-1)^i /(i! * 5^i)) by this formula we have as n -> infinity: a(n)/n! ~ sum i >= 0 (-1)^i /(i! * 5^i) = e^(-1/5) or a(n) ~ e^(-1/5) * n! and using Stirling's formula in A000142: a(n) ~ e^(-1/5) * (n/e)^n * sqrt(2 * Pi * n).
a(n,k) = n!*floor(floor(n/k)!*k^floor(n/k)/exp(1/k) + 1/2)/(floor(n/k)! * k^floor(n/k)), k=5, n>=0. - _Simon Plouffe_, Feb 18 2011

A060726.name: For n >= 1, a(n) is the number of permutations in the symmetric group S_n such that their cycle decomposition contains no 6-cycle.
formula: The formula for a(n) is: a(n) = n! * Sum_{i=0..floor(n/6)} ((-1)^i /(i! * 6^i)) by this formula we have as n -> infinity: a(n)/n! ~ Sum_{i>= 0} (-1)^i /(i! * 6^i) = e^(-1/6) or a(n) ~ e^(-1/6) * n! and using Stirling's formula in A000142: a(n) ~ e^(-1/6) * (n/e)^n * sqrt(2 * Pi * n)

A060727.name: For n >= 1 a(n) is the number of permutations in the symmetric group S_n such that their cycle decomposition contains no 7-cycle.
formula: The formula for a(n) is: a(n) = n! * sum i=0 ... [ n/7 ]( (-1)^i /(i! * 7^i)) by this formula we have as n -> infinity: a(n)/n! ~ sum i >= 0 (-1)^i /(i! * 7^i) = e^(-1/7) or a(n) ~ e^(-1/7) * n! and using Stirling's formula in A000142: a(n) ~ e^(-1/7) * (n/e)^n * sqrt(2 * Pi * n)

A060728.name: Numbers n such that Ramanujan's equation x^2 + 7 = 2^n has an integer solution.
formula: Empirically, a(n) = Fibonacci(c + 1) + 2 = ceiling[e^((c - 1)/2)] + 2 where {c} is the complete set of positive solutions to {n in N | 2 cos(2*Pi/n) is in Z}; c is in {1,2,3,4,6} (see A217290).

A060729.name: a(n+1) = a(n) + a(n minus the number of terms of the same parity as n so far).

A060730.name: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n - 1 minus the number of terms of a(k) == (mod 3) so far).

A060731.name: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n - 1 minus the number of terms of a(k) == (mod 4) so far).

A060732.name: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n - 1 minus the number of terms of a(k) == (mod 5) so far).

A060733.name: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n - 1 minus the number of terms of a(k) == (mod 6) so far).

A060734.name: Natural numbers written as a square array ending in last row from left to right and rightmost column from bottom to top are read by antidiagonals downwards.

A060735.name: Numbers k at which k / (phi(k) + 1) increases.
formula: a(1) = 1, a(n) = a(n-1) + rad(a(n-1)) with rad=A007947, squarefree kernel. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 10 2006

A060736.name: Array of square numbers read by antidiagonals in up direction.
formula: a(n)=i^2-j+1 if i >= j, a(n)=(j-1)^2 + i if i <  j, where i=n-t*(t+1)/2,

A060737.name: Number of distinct differences between consecutive divisors of n! (ordered by size).

A060738.name: Number of distinct differences between consecutive divisors (ordered by increasing magnitude) of n! which are not also divisors of n!.

A060739.name: a(n) = (-1)^(n(n-1)/2) * Product_{k=0,...,n-1} (n+k-1)!/((k!)^2 * (n-1-k)!).
formula: If Multinomial[a, b, c] denotes the multinomial coefficient (a+b+c)! / (a! * b! * c!) (which is an integer) then : a(n) = (-1)^(n(n-1)/2) * Product k=0, ..., n-1 Multinomial[k, k, n-1-k] = (-1)^(n(n-1)/2) * product k=0, ..., n-1 (n+k-1)!/((k!)^2 * (n-1-k)!)
|a(n)| ~ A^3 * 2^(2*n^2 - 3*n + 5/12) * exp(n - 1/4) / (Pi^n * n^(n - 1/4)), where A is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant A074962. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, May 19 2020

A060741.name: Number of divisors of 2n which are also differences between consecutive divisors of 2n (ordered by size).

A060742.name: Number of divisors of n! which are also differences between consecutive divisors of n! (ordered by size).

A060743.name: Least k such that gcd( p(k), q(k) ) is n, where p() is the unrestricted partition function (A000041) and q is the distinct partition function (A000009).

A060744.name: Numbers n such that n | p(n)*q(n), where p() is the unrestricted partition function (A000041) and q is the distinct partition function (A000009).

A060745.name: When gcd( p(n), q(n) ) increases, where p() is the unrestricted partition function (A000041) and q is the distinct partition function (A000009).

A060746.name: Absolute value of numerator of non-Euler-constant term of Laurent expansion of Gamma function at s=-n.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = lcm(Wolstenholme(n), n!)/n!, cf. A001008. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, May 20 2004

A060747.name: a(n) = 2*n - 1.
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) - a(n-2); a(0)=-1, a(1)=1. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 03 2008
a(n) = 4*n - a(n-1) - 4 for n>0, with a(0)=-1. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 07 2010

A060748.name: a(n) = smallest m such that the elliptic curve x^3+y^3=m has rank n, or -1 if no such m exists.

A060749.name: Triangle in which n-th row lists all primitive roots modulo the n-th prime.

A060750.name: Step at which card n appears on top of deck for first time in Guy's shuffling problem A035485.

A060751.name: These numbers take a record number of steps to reach the top of the deck in Guy's shuffle (see A060750).

A060752.name: These numbers are the record number of steps for the numbers in A060751 to reach the top of the deck in Guy's shuffle (see A060750).

A060753.name: Denominator of 1*2*4*6*...*(prime(n-1)-1) / (2*3*5*7*...*prime(n-1)).
formula: A038110(n) / a(n) ~ exp( -gamma ) / log( prime(n) ), Mertens's theorem for x = prime(n) = A000040(n).
A038110(n) / a(n) = A005867(n) / A002110(n). - corrected by _Simon Tatham_, Jul 26 2016

A060754.name: Absolute values of a certain cubic form at integer points.

A060756.name: a(n) is the smallest number for which exactly n primes are bounded between a(n) and 2a(n) exclusively.

A060762.name: Number of conjugacy classes (the same as the number of irreducible representations) in the dihedral group with 2n elements.
formula: For odd n: a(n) = (n+3)/2; for even n: a(n) = (n+6)/2.
a(1)=2,a(2)=4. For odd n:a(n)=(a(n-1)+a(n-2))/2; for even n: a(n)=(a(n-1)+a(n-2)+3)/2. [_Vincenzo Librandi_, Dec 20 2010]

A060763.name: Number of distinct differences between consecutive divisors (ordered by increasing magnitude) of n which are not also divisors of n.

A060764.name: Number of divisors of n which are not also differences between consecutive divisors (ordered by increasing magnitude) of n.

A060765.name: Numbers n such that every difference between consecutive divisors (ordered by increasing magnitude) of n is also a divisor of n.

A060766.name: Least common multiple of differences between consecutive divisors of n (ordered by size).

A060768.name: Pseudo-Kaprekar triples: q such that if q=x+y+z, then q^3=x*10^i + y*10^j + z, where (y*10^j+z < 10^i) and z < 10^j.

A060769.name: "Overdue" primes: upper ends of prime gaps that are larger than the prime number theorem predicts.
formula: A prime p belongs to the sequence iff p/log(p) - q/log(q) > 1 where q is the preceding prime.

A060770.name: "Early" primes: upper ends of prime gaps that are smaller than the prime number theorem predicts.
formula: A prime p belongs to the sequence iff p/log(p) - q/log(q) < 1 where q is the preceding prime.

A060771.name: Upper ends of record prime gaps under consideration of the prime number theorem.
formula: A prime p belongs to the sequence iff p/log(p) - q/log(q) attains a new high, where q is the preceding prime.

A060772.name: Minimal Thompson primes: a(n) is the smallest prime expressible as p1*p2*...*pk-q1*q2*...*qj, where k+j=n and {p1,...,qj} are the first n primes.

A060773.name: Numbers having a unique partition into three nonnegative triangular numbers.

A060774.name: a(n) = number of lattice paths from (0,0,0) to (n,n,n) along the cracks on the surface of a Rubik-ized n X n X n cube so that no step increases distance from goal.
formula: a(n) = 6*A000846(n) for n>0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 31 2015

A060775.name: The greatest divisor d|n such that d < n/d, with a(1) = 1.
formula: a(n) = max { d: d|n and d < sqrt(n) or d = 1 }, where "|" means "divides". [Corrected by _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 03 2019]

A060777.name: Larger central (or median) divisor of n!.

A060781.name: Numbers n such that lcm(sigma(n+1), sigma(n)) = lcm(A000203(n+1), A000203(n)).

A060782.name: Degree of the curve C(n) relative to a triangle ABC with side lengths a, b and c, given by (x^n- b^n)(y^n-c^n)(z^n-a^n)=(x^n-c^n)(y^n-a^n)(z^n-b^n) where x, y and z denote the distances from the variable point to vertices A, B and C respectively.
formula: It is known that a(n) = 2n-1 for n even; a(1) = 14; a(3) = 46; and it is conjectured that a(n) = 16n-2 for n odd.

A060783.name: Number of conics which pass through 3 points and are bitangent to a general curve of order n.

A060784.name: Number of double tangents of order n.

A060785.name: a(n) = 3*(n-2)*(5*n -11).
formula: a(n) = 30*n + a(n-1) - 78 with n>2, a(2)=0. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 07 2010

A060789.name: a(n) = n / (gcd(n,2) * gcd(n,3)).
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e)=2^(e-1), a(3^e)=3^(e-1), a(p^e)=p^e, p>3. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 09 2004
a(n) divides n. a(6k) = k for integer k>0. a(p^k) = p^k for prime p>3 and integer k>0. - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Sep 20 2006
a(n) = denominator((4*n-6)/n), n >= 2, with a(1) = 1. - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Dec 19 2012
a(n) = 2*a(n-6) - a(n-12) for n >= 12. - _Robert Israel_, Aug 06 2015
a(n) = n/b(n), where b(n) is the purely periodic sequence [1,2,3,2,1,6,...] with period 6.

A060790.name: Inscribe two circles of curvature 2 inside a circle of curvature -1. Sequence gives curvatures of the smallest circles that can be sequentially inscribed in such a diagram.
formula: Lim_{n -> inf} a(n)/a(n-1) = A318605. - _A.H.M. Smeets_, Sep 12 2018

A060791.name: a(n) = n / gcd(n,5).
formula: a(n) = n/5 if 5|n, otherwise a(n) = n.
a(n) = A109046(n)/5. Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s-1)*(1-4/5^s). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 18 2011
If gcd(n, m) = 1 then a(a(n)*a(m)) = a(a(n)) * a(a(m)), a(a(a(n))*a(a(m))) = a(a(a(n))) * a(a(a(m))) and so on.

A060792.name: Numbers that are palindromic in bases 2 and 3.

A060793.name: Orders of finite perfect groups (groups such that G = G' where G' is the commutator subgroup of G).

A060794.name: Difference between upper and lower central divisors of n.

A060795.name: Write product of first n primes as x*y with x<y and x maximal; sequence gives value of x.

A060796.name: Upper central divisor of n-th primorial.

A060797.name: Integer part of square root of n-th primorial, A002110(n).

A060798.name: Numbers k such that difference between the upper and lower central divisors of k is 1.
formula: Solutions to A033677(k) - A060775(k) = 1, where k = j*(j+1) and at least one of j and j+1 is composite.
Except at n < 5, this sequence satisfies a(n+1) = 3*a(n) - 3*a(n-1) + a(n-2). - _Georgi Guninski_, Jun 07 2010 [This follows from Corneth's theorem above. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 02 2018]
G.f.: (2*x^2-2*x+1)*(x^3-x^2-x-1) / (x-1)^3. - _Colin Barker_, Apr 16 2014 [This follows from Corneth's theorem above. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 02 2018]

A060800.name: a(n) = p^2 + p + 1 where p runs through the primes.

A060801.name: Invert transform of odd numbers: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} (2*k+1)*a(n-k), a(0)=1.

A060802.name: To weigh from 1 to n, make the heaviest weight as small as possible, under the condition of using fewest pieces of different, single weights; a(n) = weight of the heaviest weight.
formula: If 2^x <= n <= (2^x)+2 then a(n) = 2 ^ floor(base2log(x)-2)+2 (see A052548)
If (2^x)+2 < n and n+1 < (2^x + 2^x+1)/2 then a(n) and a(n+1) = a(n-1)+1
If (2^x+2^x+1)/2 <= n then a(n) = a(n-1)+1. - _David Consiglio, Jr._, Jan 08 2015

A060805.name: Numerators of special continued fraction for 2*zeta(3).

A060806.name: Denominators of special continued fraction for 2*zeta(3).

A060807.name: Numerators of ordinary continued fraction for 2*zeta(3).

A060808.name: Denominators of ordinary continued fraction for 2*zeta(3).

A060810.name: Numbers whose squares have their digits in strictly increasing order.

A060811.name: Numbers whose square has a majority of one digit.

A060812.name: Numbers whose square has a majority of one digit and does not end in 0.

A060813.name: Numbers whose square has more than 2/3 of its digits the same.

A060814.name: Numbers whose cubes contain more than half the same digit and do not end in 0.

A060815.name: Powers of 2 with each digit a power of 2 (only digits 0,1,2,4,8 are used).

A060816.name: a(0) = 1; a(n) = (5*3^(n-1) - 1)/2 for n > 0.
formula: The following is a summary of formulas added over the past 18 years.
a(n) = 3*a(n-1) + 1; with a(0)=1, a(1)=2. - _Jason Earls_, Apr 29 2001
For n > 0, a(n) = floor(3^n*5/6). - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 06 2019

A060817.name: Size of the automorphism group of the alternating group A_n.

A060818.name: a(n) = 2^(floor(n/2) + floor(n/4) + floor(n/8) + floor(n/16) + ...).
formula: a(n) = denominator(L(n)) with rational L(n):=binomial(2*n,n)/2^n. L(n) is the leading coefficient of the Legendre polynomial P_n(x).
L(n) = (2*n-1)!!/n!, with the double factorial (2*n-1)!! = A001147(n), n>=0.
a(n) = (n! XOR floor(n!/2)) XOR (n!-1 XOR floor((n!-1)/2)). - _Gary Detlefs_, Jun 13 2014
a(n) = denominator(Catalan(n-1)/2^(n-1)) for n>0. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Sep 01 2014

A060819.name: a(n) = n / gcd(n,4).
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e) = 2^max(0, e-2), a(p^e) = p^e, p >= 3. - _Mitch Harris_, Jun 29 2005
a((2*n-1)*2^p) = ceiling(2^(p-2))*(2*n-1), p >= 0 and n >= 1. - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Feb 06 2013
O.g.f.: Sum_{n >= 0} a(n)*x^n = F(x) - F(x^2) - F(x^4), where F(x) = x/(1 - x)^2.

More generally, Sum_{n >= 0} (a(n)^m)*x^n = F(m,x) + (1 - 2^m)*( F(m,x^2) + F(m,x^4) ), where F(m,x) = A(m,x)/(1 - x)^(m+1) with A(m,x) the m_th Eulerian polynomial: A(1,x) = x, A(2,x) = x*(1 + x), A(3,x) = x*(1 + 4*x + x^2) - see A008292.

Repeatedly applying the Euler operator x*d/dx or its inverse operator to the o.g.f. for the sequence a(n) produces generating functions for the sequences ((n^m)*a(n))n>=1 for m in Z. Some examples are given below.

A060821.name: Triangle T(n,k) read by rows giving coefficients of Hermite polynomial of order n (n >= 0, 0 <= k <= n).
formula: Recurrence for fixed n: T(n, k) = -(k+2)*(k+1)/(2*(n-k)) * T(n, k+2), starting with T(n, n) = 2^n. - _Ralf Stephan_, Mar 26 2016

The m-th row consecutive nonzero entries in increasing order are (-1)^(c/2)*(c+b)!/(c/2)!b!*2^b with c = m, m-2, ..., 0 and b = m-c if m is even and with c = m-1, m-3, ..., 0 with b = m-c if m is odd. For the 10th row starting at a(55) the 6 consecutive nonzero entries in order are -30240,302400,-403200,161280,-23040,1024 given by c = 10,8,6,4,2,0 and b = 0,2,4,6,8,10. - _Richard Turk_, Aug 20 2017

A060822.name: a(n) = prime(n) + n^3 + n^2 + 4n - 1.
formula: a(n) ~ n^3. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 30 2013

A060823.name: 4-wave sequence beginning with 2's with middles dropped.
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 3*a(n-2) - a(n-3) - a(n-4). - Antonio G. Astudillo (afg_astudillo(AT)lycos.com), Mar 22 2003

A060825.name: Smallest n-digit left truncatable prime of Henry VIII type.

A060826.name: a(n) is the largest number such that 3^a(n) [also 6^a(n)] divides A025487(n) (least prime signatures).

A060828.name: Size of the Sylow 3-subgroup of the symmetric group S_n.
formula: a(n) = 3^(n/2 + O(log n)). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 05 2015

A060829.name: For each y >= 1 there are only finitely many values of x >= 1 such that x-y and x+y are both squares; list all such pairs (x,y) with gcd(x,y) = 1 ordered by values of y; sequence gives x values.
formula: The solutions are given by x = r^2+2*r*k+2*k^2, y = 2*k*(k+r) with r >= 1, k >= 1, r odd, gcd(r, k) = 1.

A060831.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} (number of odd divisors of k) (cf. A001227).
formula: a(n) = n + floor(n/3) + floor(n/5) + floor(n/7) + floor(n/9) + ...
a(n) = Sum_{i=1..ceiling(n/2)} A000005(n-i+1). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 30 2013
Or, equivalently, a(n) = Sum_{j=1..floor((n+2)/2)} d(j), where d(j) is the number of divisors function A000005. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Dec 06 2020
G.f.: (1/(1 - x))*Sum_{k>=1} x^k/(1 - x^(2*k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Dec 23 2016
a(n) ~ n*(log(2*n) + 2*gamma - 1) / 2, where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 30 2019

A060832.name: a(n) = Sum_{k>0} floor(n/k!).
formula: a(n) = (e-1)*n + f(n) where f(n) < 0. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 19 2002
f is unbounded in the negative direction. The assertion that f(n) < 0 is correct, since (e-1)*n = Sum_{k>=1} n/k! is term for term >= this sequence. - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Nov 03 2005
G.f.: (1/(1 - x)) * Sum_{k>=1} x^(k!)/(1 - x^(k!)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 11 2019

A060833.name: Separate the natural numbers into disjoint sets A, B with 1 in A, such that the sum of any 2 distinct elements of the same set never equals 2^k + 2. Sequence gives elements of set A.
formula: a(1) = 1; and for n > 1: a(n) = A091067(n-1)+1. - _Antti Karttunen_, Feb 20 2015, based on _N. Sato_'s Feb 12 2013 comment above.

A060835.name: Least number of the form x^2 + y^3 (x, y positive) in n ways.

A060836.name: Number of permutations of n letters where exactly 5 change position.

A060837.name: List the positive rationals in the canonical order A020652(n)/A020653(n) and apply the Sagher map to turn them into integers.

A060838.name: Rank of elliptic curve x^3 + y^3 = n.

A060839.name: Number of solutions to x^3 == 1 mod n.
formula: Let b(n) be the number of primes dividing n which are congruent to 1 mod 3 (sequence A005088); then a(n) is 3^b(n) if n is not divisible by 9 and 3^(b(n) + 1) if n is divisible by 9.
Sequence is multiplicative. - _David W. Wilson_, Jan 06 2005

A060840.name: Number of irreducible representations of symmetric group S_n whose degree is not divisible by 3.
formula: If n = sum a_i*3^e[i] in base 3 where a_i is 0, 1, 2 then a(n) = product g(i) where if a(i) = 0 g(i) = 1, if a(i) = 1 g(i) = 3^i, if a(i) = 2 g(i) = 3^i * (3^i + 3) / 2

A060841.name: Numerator of 1/det(M) where M is the n X n matrix with M[i,j] = 1/lcm(i,j).

A060842.name: (C(2p,p)-2)/p^2 where p runs through the primes.

A060843.name: Busy Beaver problem: a(n) = maximal number of steps that an n-state Turing machine can make on an initially blank tape before eventually halting.

A060845.name: Largest prime < a nontrivial power of a prime.

A060846.name: Smallest prime > a nontrivial power of a prime.
formula: a(n) = nextprime(A025475(n+1)) = A007918(A025475(n+1)) = Min{p| p>A025475(n+1)}. [corrected by _Michel Marcus_, Aug 24 2019]

A060847.name: Difference between a nontrivial prime power (A025475) and the previous prime.

A060848.name: Difference between a nontrivial prime power (A025475) and the next prime.

A060849.name: Difference between 2 consecutive primes between which a nontrivial power of prime is found.
formula: a(n) = nextprime(A246547(n)) - prevprime(A246547(n)) = A013633(A246547(n)). [corrected by _Michel Marcus_, Mar 23 2020]

A060850.name: Array of the coefficients A(n,k) in the expansion of Product_{i>=1} 1/(1-x^i)^n  = Sum_{k>=0} A(n,k)*x^k, n >= 1, k >= 0.
formula: G.f. A(n;x) for n-th row satisfies A(n;x) = Sum_{k=1..n} A000041(k-1)*A(n-k;x)*x^(k-1), A(0;x) = 1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jan 02 2004

A060852.name: Sum of number of pips on dice in shape of Platonic solids.

A060853.name: Number of possible games of 10-pin bowling with a total score of n.

A060854.name: Array T(m,n) read by antidiagonals: T(m,n) (m >= 1, n >= 1) = number of ways to arrange the numbers 1,2,...,m*n in an m X n matrix so that each row and each column is increasing.

A060855.name: Multi-dimensional Catalan numbers: diagonal T(n,n+1) of A060854.
formula: a(n) ~ sqrt(Pi) * exp(n^2/2 + n + 7/12) * n^(n^2 + n + 11/12) / (A * 2^(2*n^2 + 2*n - 1/12)), where A = A074962 = 1.2824271291... is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 09 2015

A060856.name: Multi-dimensional Catalan numbers: diagonal T(n,n+2) of A060854.
formula: a(n) ~ sqrt(Pi) * exp(n^2/2 + 2*n + 25/12) * n^(n^2 + 2*n + 11/12) / (A * 2^(2*n^2 + 4*n + 17/12)), where A = A074962 = 1.2824271291... is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 09 2015

A060857.name: Describe all the numbers already used (sorted into increasing order - not splitting numbers up into their digits).

A060858.name: "0303456", a popular song by Rafaela Carra.

A060859.name: Powerful numbers of the form k^2 - 1 such that k^2 is also powerful.
formula: a(n) = k^2 - 1 and a(n) + 1 = k^2 are consecutive powerful numbers.

A060860.name: Numbers n such that n^2-1 and n^2 are consecutive powerful numbers.

A060861.name: Least number of the form x^2 + y^3 (x, y nonnegative) in exactly n ways.

A060862.name: a(n) = 0 if n is deficient, 1 if n is abundant, 2 if n is perfect.

A060863.name: Positive numbers n which are the average of a run of consecutive primes.

A060864.name: Positive integers that are not an average of consecutive primes.

A060865.name: a(n) is the exact power of 2 that divides the n-th Fibonacci number (A000045).
formula: If n is not divisible by 3 then a(n) = 1, if n = 3 * 2^k * (2m + 1) then a(n) = 2 if k=0 or 2^(k+2) if k>0.
a(n) = F(n) / A174883(n). - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Jan 24 2012

A060866.name: Sum of (d+d') over all unordered pairs (d,d') with d*d' = n.

A060867.name: a(n) = (2^n - 1)^2.
formula: a(n) = sum_{j=1..n} sum_{k=1..n} binomial(n+j,n-k). - _Yalcin Aktar_, Dec 28 2011

A060868.name: Number of n X n matrices over GF(3) with rank 1.

A060869.name: Number of n X n matrices over GF(4) with rank 1.

A060870.name: Number of n X n matrices over GF(5) with rank 1.

A060871.name: Number of n X n matrices over GF(7) with rank 1.

A060872.name: Sum of d*d' over all unordered pairs (d,d') with d*d' = n.
formula: a(n) = n * ceiling( d(n)/2) where d is the number of divisors function.
G.f.: x*f'(x), where f(x) = Sum_{k>=1} x^k^2/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 10 2017

A060873.name: Intrinsic 3-palindromes: n is an intrinsic k-palindrome if it is a k-digit palindrome in some base.

A060874.name: Intrinsic 4-palindromes: n is an intrinsic k-palindrome if it is a k-digit palindrome in some base.

A060875.name: Intrinsic 5-palindromes: n is an intrinsic k-palindrome if it is a k-digit palindrome in some base.

A060878.name: Intrinsic 8-palindromes: n is an intrinsic k-palindrome if it is a k-digit palindrome in some base.

A060879.name: Intrinsic 9-palindromes: n is an intrinsic k-palindrome if it is a k-digit palindrome in some base.

A060882.name: a(n) = n-th primorial (A002110) minus next prime.

A060890.name: n^8 + 1.
formula: Sum_{n>=0} 1/a(n) = 1/2 + Pi*((sqrt(2 + sqrt(2)) * sin(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi) + sqrt(2 - sqrt(2)) * sinh(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi)) / (cosh(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi) - cos(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi)) + (sqrt(2 - sqrt(2)) * sin(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi) + sqrt(2 + sqrt(2)) * sinh(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi)) / (cosh(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi) - cos(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi))) / 8 = 1.5040621333147995112929... . - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 14 2015

Sum_{n>=0} (-1)^n/a(n) = 1/2 + Pi*((sqrt(2 - sqrt(2)) * sin(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi/2) - sqrt(2 + sqrt(2)) * sinh(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi/2)) / (cos(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi/2) + cosh(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi/2)) - (sqrt(2 - sqrt(2)) * sin(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi/2) + sqrt(2 + sqrt(2)) * sinh(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi/2)) / (cos(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi/2) - cosh(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi/2)) + (sqrt(2 + sqrt(2)) * sin(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi/2) - sqrt(2 - sqrt(2)) * sinh(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi/2)) / (cos(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi/2) + cosh(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi/2)) - (sqrt(2 + sqrt(2)) * sin(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi/2) + sqrt(2 - sqrt(2)) * sinh(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi/2)) / (cos(sqrt(2 + sqrt(2))*Pi/2) - cosh(sqrt(2 - sqrt(2))*Pi/2)))/16 = 0.5037518217314416642671664241... . - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 14 2015

A060897.name: Number of walks of length n on square lattice, starting at origin, staying in first and third quadrants.

A060898.name: Number of walks of length n on square lattice, starting at origin, staying in first, second and third quadrants.

A060899.name: Number of walks of length n on square lattice, starting at origin, staying on points with x+y >= 0.
formula: a(n) = 4^n*sum{k=0..n, C(n,k)C(k)/(-2)^k}, with C(n)=A000108(n). - _Paul Barry_, Dec 28 2006

A060900.name: Number of walks of length n on square lattice, starting at origin, staying on points with x >= 0, y <= x.
formula: The following conjectural formula for this sequence is apparently due to _Ira M. Gessel_: a(0) = 1, a(2n) = a(2n-1)*(12n+2)/(3n+1), a(2n+1) = a(2n)*(4n+2)/(n+1).

A060901.name: Exact power of 3 that divides the n-th Fibonacci number (sequence A000045).
formula: If n is not divisible by 4 then a(n) = 1, if n = 4 * 3^k * m where m is not divisible by 3 then a(n) = 3^(k+1).

A060902.name: Number of ordered factorizations of the identity permutation in the symmetric group S_n into 2n-2 transpositions such that the factors generate S_n.

A060904.name: Largest power of 5 that divides n.
formula: If n is not divisible by 5, then a(n) = 1. If n = 5^k * m where m is not divisible by 5, then a(n) = 5^k.
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*(5^s-1)/(5^s-5). - _R. J. Mathar_, Jul 12 2012

A060905.name: E.g.f.: exp(x*exp(x) + 1/2*x^2*exp(x)^2).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(Sum_{d|m} T_k^d/d), where T_k = x*exp(T_(k - 1)), k >= 1, T_0 = x; k = 1, m = 2.

A060906.name: E.g.f.: exp(x*exp(x) + 1/3*x^3*exp(x)^3).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(Sum_{d|m} T_k^d/d), where T_k = x*exp(T_(k - 1)), k >= 1, T_0 = x; k = 1, m = 3.

A060907.name: E.g.f.: exp(x*exp(x) + 1/2*x^2*exp(x)^2 + 1/4*x^4*exp(x)^4).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(Sum_{d|m} T_k^d/d), where T_k = x*exp(T_(k - 1)), k >= 1, T_0 = x; k = 1, m = 4.

A060908.name: E.g.f.: exp(x*exp(x*exp(x)) + 1/2*x^2*exp(x*exp(x))^2).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(Sum_{d|m} T_k^d/d), where T_k = x*exp(T_(k - 1)), k >= 1, T_0 = x; k = 2, m = 2.

A060909.name: E.g.f.: exp(x*exp(x*exp(x)) + 1/3*x^3*exp(x*exp(x))^3).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(Sum_{d|m} T_k^d/d), where T_k = x*exp(T_(k - 1)), k >= 1, T_0 = x; k = 2, m = 3.

A060910.name: E.g.f.: exp(x*exp(x*exp(x)) + 1/2*x^2*exp(x*exp(x))^2 + 1/4*x^4*exp(x*exp(x))^4).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(Sum_{d|m} T_k^d/d), where T_k = x*exp(T_(k - 1)), k >= 1, T_0 = x; k = 2, m = 4.

A060911.name: E.g.f.: exp(x*exp(x*exp(x*exp(x))) + 1/2*x^2*exp(x*exp(x*exp(x)))^2).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(Sum_{d|m} T_k^d/d), where T_k = x*exp(T_(k - 1)), k >= 1, T_0 = x; k = 3, m = 2.

A060912.name: E.g.f.: exp(x*exp(x*exp(x*exp(x*exp(x)))) + 1/2*x^2*exp(x*exp(x*exp(x*exp(x))))^2).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(Sum_{d|m} T_k^d/d), where T_k = x*exp(T_(k - 1)), k >= 1, T_0 = x; k = 4, m = 2.

A060913.name: E.g.f.: exp(x*exp(x*exp(x*exp(x))) + 1/3*x^3*exp(x*exp(x*exp(x)))^3).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(Sum_{d|m} T_k^d/d), where T_k = x*exp(T_(k - 1)), k >= 1, T_0 = x; k = 3, m = 3.

A060914.name: Integers i > 1 for which there are two primes p such that i is a solution mod p of x^3 = 2.
formula: a(n) = n-th integer i such that i^3 - 2 has two prime factors > i.

A060915.name: Similar to A060399, but more than one digit may be taken (in order) from each prime.

A060916.name: Similar to A060400, but more than one digit may be taken (in order) from each prime.

A060919.name: Number of corners in a 4-sided fractal.

A060920.name: Bisection of Fibonacci triangle A037027: even-indexed members of column sequences of A037027 (not counting leading zeros).
formula: T(n, 0) = F(n)^2 + F(n+1)^2 = A001519(n), with the Fibonacci numbers F(n) = A000045(n).
G.f. for column m >= 0: x^m*pFe(m+1, x)/(1-3*x+x^2)^(m+1), where pFe(n, x) := Sum_{m=0..n} A061176(n, m)*x^m (row polynomials of signed triangle A061176).

A060921.name: Bisection of Fibonacci triangle A037027: odd-indexed members of column sequences of A037027 (not counting leading zeros).
formula: G.f. for column m >= 0: x^m*pFo(m+1, x)/(1-3*x+x^2)^(m+1), where pFo(n, x) := Sum_{m=0..n-1} A061177(n-1, m)*x^m (row polynomials of signed triangle A061177).

A060922.name: Convolution triangle for Lucas numbers A000032(n+1), n >= 0.

A060923.name: Bisection of Lucas triangle A060922: even indexed members of column sequences of A060922 (not counting leading zeros).
formula: G.f. for column m >= 0: x^m*pLe(m+1, x)/(1-3*x+x^2)^(m+1), where pLe(n, x) := sum(A061186(n, m)*x^m, m=0..n+floor(n/2)) are the row polynomials of the (signed) staircase A061186.

A060924.name: Bisection of Lucas triangle A060922: odd-indexed members of column sequences of A060922 (not counting leading zeros).
formula: G.f. for column m >= 0: x^m*pLo(m+1, x)/(1-3*x+x^2)^(m+1), where pLo(n, x) := Sum_{m=0..n+floor((n-1)/2)} A061187(n-1, m)*x^m are the row polynomials of the (signed) staircase A061187.

A060925.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 3*a(n-2), a(0) = 1, a(1) = 4.
formula: Row sums of Lucas convolution triangle A060922.
Inverse binomial transform of A003947. - _Philippe Deléham_, Jul 23 2005
Binomial transform is A003947. - _Paul Barry_, May 19 2003

A060926.name: Row sums of triangle A060923 (even part of bisection of Lucas triangle).

A060927.name: Row sums of triangle A060924 (odd part of bisection of Lucas triangle).

A060929.name: Second convolution of Lucas numbers A000032(n+1), n >= 0.
formula: a(n) = A060922(n+2, 2) (third column of Lucas triangle).

A060930.name: Third convolution of Lucas numbers A000032(n+1), n >= 0.
formula: a(n) = A060922(n+3, 3) (fourth column of Lucas triangle).

A060931.name: Fourth convolution of Lucas numbers A000032(n+1), n >= 0.
formula: a(n) = A060921(n+4, 4) (fifth column of Lucas triangle).

A060932.name: Fifth convolution of Lucas numbers A000032(n+1), n >= 0.
formula: a(n) = A060922(n+5, 5) (sixth column of Lucas triangle).

A060933.name: Sixth convolution of Lucas numbers A000032(n+1), n >= 0.
formula: a(n) = A060922(n+6, 6) (seventh column of Lucas triangle).

A060934.name: Second column of Lucas bisection triangle (even part).

A060935.name: Sum of entries in n-th antidiagonal in A060854.

A060936.name: Multiples of 3 with digits grouped in pairs and leading zeros omitted.

A060937.name: Number of iterations of d(n) (A000005) needed to reach 2 starting at n (n is counted).

A060938.name: Maximal degree of an irreducible representation of a group with n elements.

A060939.name: a(n) = (Sum of the first n primes) + n.
formula: a(n) = A007504(n) + n. - _Omar E. Pol_, Dec 30 2013

A060940.name: Triangle in which n-th row gives the phi(n) terms appearing as initial primes in arithmetic progressions with difference n, with initial term equal to the smallest positive residue coprimes to n.

A060941.name: Duchon's numbers: the number of paths of length 5*n from the origin to the line y = 2*x/3 with unit East and North steps that stay below the line or touch it.
formula: G.f. A(z) satisfies: A(z) = 1+2*z*A^5-z*A^6+z*A^7+z^2*A^10. [Corrected by _Bryan T. Ek_, Oct 30 2017]

Asymptotics (Duchon, 2000): a(n) ~ c * (3125/108)^n / n^(3/2), where c = 0.0876612192439026461763141944768209255550234422281635788... (constant corrected, in the reference "On the enumeration and generation of generalized Dyck words", p.132 is wrong value 0.0887). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 05 2014

O.g.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x)^5 = 1/x*series reversion( x/((1+x)*C(x))^5 ), where C(x) = (1 - sqrt(1 - 4*x))/(2*x) is the o.g.f. for the Catalan numbers A000108. See A001450. - _Peter Bala_, Oct 05 2015

A060942.name: a(n) is the largest integer m such that m is divisible by every integer in the interval 1 <= x <= m^(1/n).

A060943.name: a(n) = n!^n * Sum_{k=1..n} 1/k^n.
formula: a(n) = (n!)^n * [x^n] PolyLog(n,x)/(1 - x), where PolyLog() is the polylogarithm function. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 27 2017

A060944.name: a(n) = n!^2 * Sum_{k=1..n} Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j^2.
formula: a(n) = (n!)^2 * Sum_{k=1..n} HarmonicNumber(k, 2), where HarmonicNumber(k, 2) = A007406(k) / A007407(k). (End)
Sum_{n>=1} a(n) * x^n / (n!)^2 = polylog(2,x) / (1 - x)^2. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 15 2020

A060945.name: Number of compositions (ordered partitions) of n into 1's, 2's and 4's.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} Sum_{i=0..n-k} C(i, n-k-i)*C(2*i-n+k, 3*k-2*n+2*i). - _Paul Barry_, Oct 24 2005
a(2n) = A238236(n), a(2n+1) = A097472(n). - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 20 2014

A060946.name: Trace of Vandermonde matrix of numbers 1,2,...,n, i.e., the matrix A with A[i,j] = i^(j-1), 1 <= i <= n, 1 <= j <= n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} A000169(k). - _Jonathan Vos Post_, Feb 12 2010

A060947.name: Intrinsic 10-palindromes: n is an intrinsic k-palindrome if it is a k-digit palindrome in some base.

A060948.name: Intrinsic 11-palindromes: n is an intrinsic k-palindrome if it is a k-digit palindrome in some base.

A060949.name: Intrinsic 12-palindromes: n is an intrinsic k-palindrome if it is a k-digit palindrome in some base.

A060950.name: Rank of elliptic curve y^2 = x^3 + n.
formula: a(n) = A060951(27*n) and A060951(n) = a(27*n), so a(n) = a(729*n). - _Jonathan Sondow_, Sep 10 2013

A060951.name: Rank of elliptic curve y^2 = x^3 - n.
formula: a(n) = A060950(27*n) and A060950(n) = a(27*n), so a(n) = a(729*n). - _Jonathan Sondow_, Sep 10 2013

A060952.name: Rank of elliptic curve y^2 = x^3 - n*x.

A060953.name: Rank of elliptic curve y^2 = x^3 + n*x.

A060955.name: Highest degree of an irreducible representation of the alternating group A_n of degree n.

A060957.name: Number of different products (including the empty product) of any subset of {1, 2, 3, ..., n}.

A060958.name: Gregorian Easter dates, starting after 2000-04-23, a(2000) = 54.

A060959.name: Table by antidiagonals of generalized Fibonacci numbers: T(n,k) = T(n,k-1) + n*T(n,k-2) with T(n,0)=0 and T(n,1)=1.

A060961.name: Number of compositions (ordered partitions) of n into 1's, 3's and 5's.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{m=floor((n+1)/2)..n} (Sum_{j=0..2*m-n} binomial(j,3*n-5*m+2*j)*binomial(2*m-n,j))), n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Mar 11 2013

A060963.name: Number of pairings of the first 2n positive integers so that the absolute differences of each pair are different.

A060964.name: Table by antidiagonals where T(n,k) = n*T(n,k-1) - T(n,k-2) with T(n,0) = 2 and T(n,1) = n.
formula: For all m, T(n, k) = T(n, |m|)*T(n, |k - m|) - T(n, |k - 2m|).
T(n, k) = n*ChebyshevU(k-1, n/2) - 2*ChebyshevU(k-2, n/2). - _G. C. Greubel_, Jan 15 2020

A060965.name: For p=prime(n), a(n) = number of points (x,y) on the elliptic curve x^3 + y^3 = 1 (mod p), including the point at infinity.

A060966.name: Number of nonisomorphic circulant oriented graphs (i.e., Cayley graphs for the cyclic group) of order n.

A060968.name: Number of solutions to x^2 + y^2 == 1 (mod n).
formula: Multiplicative, with a(2^e) = 2 if e = 1 or 2^(e+1) if e > 1, a(p^e) = (p-1)p^(e-1) if p == 1 (mod 4), a(p^e) = (p+1)p^(e-1) if p == 3 (mod 4). - _David W. Wilson_, Jun 19 2001
a(n) = n * product{ 1 - 1/p, p is prime, p | n and p = 1 mod 4 } * product{ 1 + 1/p, p is prime, p | n and p = 3 mod 4 } * {2, if 4 | n }. - Ola Veshta (olaveshta(AT)my-deja.com), May 18 2001

A060970.name: Number of fourth powers of primes <= 2^n.

A060971.name: Number of numbers of form p^5, p prime, <= 2^n.

A060972.name: Triangle giving numbers of closed plane meanders.

A060975.name: Irregular primes with irregularity index three.

A060976.name: Odd nonprimes c which divide Bernoulli(2*c).

A060977.name: The nonprimes n!+2 ... n!+n are the a(n)-th string of n-1 prime-free consecutive terms, the first such one being the string of composite numbers A000230(k)+1 through A001632(k)-1 when n=2k, or through A001632(k)-2 when n=2k-1.

A060978.name: |First digit - second digit + third digit - fourth digit ...| = 10.

A060979.name: |First digit - second digit + third digit - fourth digit ...| = 11.

A060980.name: |First digit - second digit + third digit - fourth digit ...| = 12.

A060982.name: Smallest nontrivial number m such that |first digit - second digit + third digit - fourth digit ...| = n.

A060983.name: Number of primitive sublattices of index n in generic 3-dimensional lattice.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s) * zeta(s-1) * zeta(s-2) / zeta(3s).
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ Pi^2 * Zeta(3) * n^3 / (18*Zeta(9)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 01 2019

A060985.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) = a(n) + (largest triangular number <= a(n)).

A060986.name: Viggo Brun's ternary continued fraction algorithm applied to { log 2, log 3/2, log 5/4 } produces a list of triples (p,q,r); sequence gives p values.

A060987.name: Viggo Brun's ternary continued fraction algorithm applied to { log 2, log 3/2, log 5/4 } produces a list of triples (p,q,r); sequence gives q values.

A060988.name: Viggo Brun's ternary continued fraction algorithm applied to { log 2, log 3/2, log 5/4 } produces a list of triples (p,q,r); sequence gives r values.

A060989.name: Number of nice error bases of degree n with a non-Abelian index group.

A060990.name: Number of solutions to x - d(x) = n, where d(n) is the number of divisors of n (A000005).
formula: a(0) = 2; for n >= 1, a(n) = Sum_{k = n .. n+A002183(2+A261100(n))} [A049820(k) = n]. (Here [...] denotes the Iverson bracket, resulting 1 when A049820(k) is n and 0 otherwise.) - _Antti Karttunen_, Sep 25 2015, corrected Oct 12 2015.
a(n) = Sum_{k = A082284(n) .. A262686(n)} [A049820(k) = n] (when tacitly assuming that A049820(0) = 0.) - _Antti Karttunen_, Oct 12 2015
Other identities and observations. For all n >= 0:

A060991.name: a(n) is the smallest positive integer c such that the equation A049820(x) = c has exactly n solutions.

A060992.name: a(n) = Sum_{gcd(i,j) | 0 < i <= j < n and i+j = n}.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d divides n} floor(d/2)*phi(n/d). a(p) = (p-1)/2 for an odd prime p. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 21 2004
a(n) = Sum_{i=1..floor(n/2)} gcd(n-i,i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Nov 12 2017
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} phi(k)*x^(2*k)/((1 + x^k)*(1 - x^k)^2). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 24 2018

A060993.name: Radii of Integer Distance Skew Tetrahedra.

A060995.name: Number of routes of length 2n on the sides of an octagon from a point to opposite point.
formula: G.f.: G(0)/(2*x) - 1/x, where G(k)= 1 + 1/( 1 - 4*x^2/(4*x^2 + 2*(1-2*x)^2/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 16 2013

A060998.name: Squares of 1 and primes, written backwards.

A060999.name: Nearest integer to (n+1)^3/9.
formula: Expansion of x * (1 - x^4) / ((1 - x)^3 * (1 - x^2) * (1 - x^3)) in powers of x.
Euler transform of length 4 sequence [ 3, 1, 1, -1]. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 12 2009

A061000.name: x.v where x = first n terms of A060999, v = [1,8,27,...,n^3].
